Fast re-entering orbits were also reported in the literature [55, 33] for high initial eccentricities and inclinations at geosynchronous altitude. Therefore, we would like to further explore under which conditions those orbits appear and study their properties. In Fig. 10 a set of disposal maps for 63◦ inclination is presented, however, the colormap here does not correspond to the eccentricity diameter but rather to the orbital lifetime. The results are shown for four different values of the initial eccentricity e = 0.01, e = 0.1, e = 0.2, e = 0.3. For values of the eccentricity higher than 0.1 there exists, around an initial right ascension of the ascending node of Ω = 230◦, a set of orbits with very promising lifetimes of 20 − 30 years.


